<Link id="l00673" /><CodeLine lineNumber="673"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00674" /><CodeLine lineNumber="674"><Highlight kind="comment">/// A list of DIE values.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00675" /><CodeLine lineNumber="675"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00676" /><CodeLine lineNumber="676"><Highlight kind="comment">/// This is a singly-linked list, but instead of reversing the order of</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00677" /><CodeLine lineNumber="677"><Highlight kind="comment">/// insertion, we keep a pointer to the back of the list so we can push in</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00678" /><CodeLine lineNumber="678"><Highlight kind="comment">/// order.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00679" /><CodeLine lineNumber="679"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00680" /><CodeLine lineNumber="680"><Highlight kind="comment">/// There are two main reasons to choose a linked list over a customized</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00681" /><CodeLine lineNumber="681"><Highlight kind="comment">/// vector-like data structure.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00682" /><CodeLine lineNumber="682"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00683" /><CodeLine lineNumber="683"><Highlight kind="comment">///  1 For teardown efficiency, we want DIEs to be BumpPtrAllocated.  Using a</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00684" /><CodeLine lineNumber="684"><Highlight kind="comment">///     linked list here makes this way easier to accomplish.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00685" /><CodeLine lineNumber="685"><Highlight kind="comment">///  2 Carrying an extra pointer per \\a DIEValue isn&#39;t expensive.  45% of DIEs</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00686" /><CodeLine lineNumber="686"><Highlight kind="comment">///     have 2 or fewer values, and 90% have 5 or fewer.  A vector would be</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00687" /><CodeLine lineNumber="687"><Highlight kind="comment">///     over-allocated by 50% on average anyway, the same cost as the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00688" /><CodeLine lineNumber="688"><Highlight kind="comment">///     linked-list node.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00689" /><CodeLine lineNumber="689" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/dievaluelist"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">class </Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"><a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/dievaluelist">DIEValueList</a> &#123;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00690" /><CodeLine lineNumber="690"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">struct </Highlight><Highlight kind="normal">Node : <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/intrusivebacklistnode">IntrusiveBackListNode</a> &#123;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00691" /><CodeLine lineNumber="691"><Highlight kind="normal">    <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/dievalue">DIEValue</a> V;</Highlight></CodeLine>
